nutritional components: Per 100 grams contains about 27 calories, 0.41 grams of carbohydrates, 2.20 grams of fat, 2.80 grams of protein, and 1.70 grams of fiber. In addition, it contains various vitamins and minerals.

name: Tiger hazelnut
nutritional components: Contains high levels of fat, protein, and fiber.

name: Black Walnut
nutritional components: Black walnut kernels are rich in protein and fat, with protein content reaching about 28%. They also contain vitamins, calcium, iron, and other nutrients.

name: Torreya
nutritional components: Per 100 grams, it contains 6.4 grams of water, 10 grams of protein, 44.1 grams of fat (mainly unsaturated fatty acids), 29.8 grams of carbohydrates, 6.8 grams of crude fiber, and various minerals and vitamins such as calcium, phosphorus, and iron.

name: Red Maple
nutritional components: Its leaves are rich in minerals and organic acids, potentially having medicinal value. The resin of the red maple can be extracted for essential oils, commonly used in food and fragrances.

name: Ginkgo
nutritional components: Ginkgo kernels contain various nutrients, including starch, protein, fat, sugars, as well as vitamin C, riboflavin, carotene, calcium, phosphorus, iron, potassium, magnesium, and trace elements. They also contain ginkgolic acid, bilobol, pentosan polysaccharides, and sterols. The seeds of ginkgo can be used to extract ginkgo oil, which has certain medicinal value and is often used in health care.

name: Neem
nutritional components: The seeds, leaves, and bark of the neem tree are widely used as herbal medicine in regions around India. The seeds have laxative and anthelmintic properties and can treat gastric ulcers. The bark has astringent and hemostatic effects and is used to treat cancer, pain, spleen, and liver diseases. Neem oil is used to treat rheumatism.

name: Camellia
nutritional components: Camellia oil is rich in unsaturated fatty acids, especially monounsaturated fatty acids (such as oleic acid), and contains various vitamins and minerals.

name: Yew
nutritional components: The medicinal value of the yew tree is mainly reflected in its extract—secondary metabolic derivatives—paclitaxel.

name: Chives
nutritional components: Vitamin C, volatile oils, niacin, vitamin B1, vitamin B2, vitamin A, fatty acids, etc.

name: Alfalfa
nutritional components: Alfalfa contains a wide variety of vitamins, especially high levels of folic acid, chlorophyll, VK, biotin, VE, VB2, lutein, and carotene. It also contains various mineral elements such as calcium, phosphorus, iron, magnesium, potassium, copper, and manganese.

name: Vanilla
nutritional components: Typically rich in various vitamins and minerals, such as vitamin A, C, E, and trace elements like calcium, iron, and zinc. Additionally, it contains polyphenols and volatile oils.

name: Bitter Buckwheat
nutritional components: Tartary buckwheat has high nutritional value, containing protein, bioflavonoids, various vitamins, fiber, 18 amino acids, chlorophyll, and multiple components such as magnesium, potassium, calcium, iron, manganese, zinc, chromium, copper, and selenium. It is the only crop in the cereal family that combines seven major nutrients.

name: Angelica dahurica
nutritional components: Protein, vitamins, minerals, dietary fiber, polyphenols, flavonoids, etc.

name: Zelkova
nutritional components: The fruit contains 20%-40% oil, including fatty acids such as capric acid, caprylic acid, lauric acid, oleic acid, palmitic acid, and linoleic acid.

name: White wax tree
nutritional components: Rich in bioactive components such as lignin, triterpenoids, and polysaccharides. These components have special effects on human health, such as enhancing immunity, delaying cell aging, antioxidant, and anti-tumor properties.

name: Cleome
nutritional components: Per 100 grams of Cleome gynandra, it contains 12 mg of Vitamin C, 26 mg of Calcium, 6 mg of Phosphorus, 152 mg of Potassium, 215.7 mg of Sodium, 33 mg of Magnesium, 0.6 mg of Iron, 0.18 mg of Zinc, etc. Additionally, it contains a certain amount of water, protein, fat, and carbohydrates.

name: Syringa vulgaris
nutritional components: Its fresh flowers can be used to extract an oleoresin with solvents, from which essential oil can be obtained. This essential oil is a good flavoring agent for the food, cosmetics, and pharmaceutical industries. Some scholars have optimized the extraction process of Syringa vulgaris essential oil and found that the oil extracted by the refining method has high purity, few impurities, abundant aromatic substances, strong fragrance, and excellent quality, with broad application prospects and certain scientific and economic value. Additionally, the young leaves of Syringa vulgaris can be used as a tea substitute.

name: Ulmus pumila
nutritional components: The plant contains beta-sitosterol, phytol, stigmasterol, and other sterols, as well as tannins, gum, and fatty oils. It is propagated by seed, and mature fruits are sown immediately after collection.

name: Hazelnut
nutritional components: Fats: Rich in healthy fats, including monounsaturated fatty acids, polyunsaturated fatty acids, and saturated fatty acids.

name: Pecan
nutritional components: Pecans mainly consist of linoleic acid glycerides, which can soften blood vessels, prevent vascular hardening, hypertension, and coronary heart disease. The trace elements zinc and manganese in pecans are also important components of the pituitary gland. Regular consumption of pecans can enhance brain function and intelligence.

name: Peanut
nutritional components: Peanuts contain over 50% oleic acid, which is beneficial for cardiovascular health, helps reduce harmful cholesterol and high blood lipids, while maintaining or even increasing beneficial cholesterol.

name: Camellia oleifera
nutritional components: Tea oil made from Camellia oleifera contains over 90% unsaturated fatty acids such as oleic acid, linoleic acid, and linolenic acid, and is rich in nutrients like vitamin A and vitamin E. It has a golden color and a fragrant taste, with excellent properties similar to olive oil, earning it the reputation as the 'Oriental Olive Oil' and is a high-quality edible oil.

name: Cornus officinalis
nutritional components: When comparing various plants, Cornus walteri has relatively low levels of trace elements such as Fe, Zn, Cu, Mn, Cr, and Ni. For example, the Fe content is 201.53 mg/kg, Zn content is 4.73 mg/kg, Cu content is 0 (or undetectably low), Mn content is 8.13 mg/kg, Cr content is 0.36 mg/kg, and Ni content is 1.22 mg/kg. The total trace element content is also low, at 241.83 mg/kg.

name: Xanthoceras sorbifolium
nutritional components: Minerals: Rich in calcium, phosphorus, iron, and other minerals, which have positive effects on bone health, blood circulation, and nerve conduction.

name: Prunus pedunculata
nutritional components: Protein and Fat: The kernel contains 255.9 g/kg of crude protein and 531 g/kg of crude fat.

name: Acer truncatum
nutritional components: Oil: The kernel has a high oil content, with excellent oil quality, rich in essential fatty acids such as oleic acid and linoleic acid.

name: Idesia polycarpa
nutritional components: Vitamins: Rich in vitamin E and B vitamins.

name: Plukenetia volubilis
nutritional components: The oil from Plukenetia volubilis seeds is edible. The seeds are extremely rich in unsaturated fatty acids (ω-3, ω-6, ω-9), vitamin E, vitamin A, protein, and polyphenols. The content of the three unsaturated fatty acids is over 92%, earning it the titles of 'World Plant Nutrition Longevity Fruit King' and 'Plant Brain Gold'.

name: Elaeagnus mollis oil
nutritional components: The seeds contain oil, with the kernel containing 46.58-51.4% crude fat, and an oil yield of 30-35%.

name: Xikang Almond
nutritional components: The kernels of Xikang Almond can be pressed for oil, with a kernel oil content of 45.95% and an oil yield of over 40.00%. The oil is orange-yellow, clear, and transparent, suitable for edible use. The shells are an important raw material for producing high-quality activated carbon. The wood is hard and can be used for various carvings. The tree's bast fibers are long and fine, suitable for papermaking and the production of artificial cotton. The fruit pits can also be used for crafts and toys.

name: Desert Nut
nutritional components: Desert Nut is rich in nutrients. In addition to protein, fat, and carbohydrates, the kernels contain abundant carotene, vitamin B1, vitamin B2, and vitamin E. The kernels contain all eight essential amino acids required by the human body, with levels far exceeding those in walnuts. The kernels also have higher calcium, phosphorus, and iron content compared to other nuts.

name: Almond
nutritional components: Rich in fat, protein, vitamins, and minerals.

name: Sweet Almond
nutritional components: Almonds are rich in protein, fat, carbohydrates, carotene, B vitamins, vitamin C, vitamin P, as well as calcium, phosphorus, and iron. The carotene content in almonds is second only to mangoes among fruits, earning them the title of 'anti-cancer fruit.' Almonds contain abundant fatty oils, which help lower cholesterol, making them beneficial for preventing and treating cardiovascular diseases.

name: Hairy-leaf Idesia
nutritional components: The fruit has an oil content of 20%-30%, and the seeds have an oil content of 20%-26%. It can be used for making box boards and matchboxes, as well as for producing soap or lubricating oil. It is an excellent raw material for high-quality edible oil, premium skincare soap, and health products.

name: Butterfly Fruit
nutritional components: The seeds are rich in oil and starch. After detoxification, they can be eaten. The cotyledons can be boiled or stir-fried, or ground into powder and mixed into dishes as oil. They can also be extracted for use as cooking oil, with a flavor resembling a mix of sesame oil and peanut oil.

name: Sacha Inchi
nutritional components: Omega-3 fatty acids. Sacha Inchi oil is rich in essential fatty acids that are highly compatible with the skin. It contains abundant vitamin E and antioxidants.

name: Cocoa

name: Coptis
nutritional components: Pistacia chinensis is an excellent woody oilseed tree species, characterized by high oil yield and good oil quality. Research results have shown that the seed oil content is 42.26% (kernel oil content is 56.5%), seed oil yield is 20-30%, and the shell oil content is 3.28%. It is a non-drying oil with a light yellow-green color and a bitter taste, which can be used after refining. Fresh leaves contain 0.12% aromatic oil, which can be used as a health food additive and incense. The fatty acids mainly include palmitic acid, oleic acid, linoleic acid, palmitoleic acid, stearic acid, arachidonic acid, and linolenic acid. The combined content of oleic acid, linoleic acid, and palmitic acid accounts for about 95% of the total fatty acids.

name: Moringa

name: Catechu
nutritional components: The decoction of heartwood fragments, after concentration and drying, becomes catechu extract or catechu powder, which has functions such as clearing heat, promoting fluid production, resolving phlegm, stopping bleeding, healing sores, promoting tissue regeneration, and relieving pain. The tannin extracted from the heartwood is also an excellent raw material for leather tanning and dyeing in industry. The wood is hard and fine, suitable for use in sleepers, construction, agricultural tools, and carriages.

name: Tea Maple
nutritional components: The bark, leaves, and fruits of this subspecies contain tannins, which can be extracted to make tannin extract and also used as a black dye. The fibers in the bark can be used as raw materials for artificial cotton and papermaking. The dried young leaves can be used as a substitute for tea, which has the effect of lowering blood pressure. It is also a special beverage for silk workers in summer, as sweat falling on silk after consumption does not leave yellow spots. The seeds can be pressed for oil, which can be used to make soap.

name: Antidesma montanum
nutritional components: It grows in sparse forests at altitudes of 140-1500 meters. The leaves of Antidesma can be used to make a bath or drink, which is believed to ward off evil spirits and diseases, promoting health and well-being.

name: Camellia ptilophylla
nutritional components: It grows under forests or in shrublands. On dry and poor gravel soil, the plants are dwarfed, and the leaves become thinner. Those growing by streams or in dense forests can reach 3-4 meters in height, with leaves up to 8 cm long. It is recorded that the bark of this genus has fever-reducing effects, but this remains to be proven.

name: Apocynum venetum
nutritional components: This species is a widely distributed wild fiber plant in China. The stem bark fibers are long, flexible, lustrous, and resistant to decay, wear, and tension, making them suitable for high-end clothing, fishing nets, leather threads, and high-quality paper. They are also used in national defense, aviation, maritime, tire cord fabric, machine transmission belts, rubber boats, and high-end raincoats. The leaves contain 4-5% gum, which is used as a raw material for tires. The young leaves can be steamed, fried, and rolled to make tea, which has cooling, anti-inflammatory, and heart-strengthening effects. The white, silky seed hairs can be used as filling material. The peeled stems can be used as insulating building materials. The roots contain alkaloids for medicinal use. The plant has many beautiful, fragrant flowers with a long blooming period and well-developed nectaries, making it a good source of nectar.

name: Stephania tetrandra
nutritional components: The roots and stems of this plant contain various alkaloids, such as berberine and palmatine, etc. It is commonly used as an antipyretic in Hainan folk medicine and also has good anti-inflammatory effects.

name: Bai Liang Jin
nutritional components: The roots and leaves have the effects of clearing heat, soothing the throat, relaxing tendons, and promoting blood circulation. They are used to treat sore throat, tonsillitis, nephritis edema, rheumatism, and injuries. They are also used to treat turbid urine, bone tuberculosis, cough with blood from overwork, abscesses, and snake bites. The fruit is edible; the seeds can be pressed for oil.

name: Bei Ma Dou Ling
nutritional components: This species is used medicinally. The stems and leaves are called Tian Xian Teng, which have the effects of promoting qi circulation, treating blood disorders, relieving pain, and diuresis. The fruit is called Ma Dou Ling, which has the effects of clearing heat, lowering qi, relieving cough, and calming asthma. The root is called Qing Mu Xiang, which is slightly toxic and has the effects of strengthening the stomach, regulating qi, relieving pain, and lowering blood pressure.

name: Ying Zhao Hua
nutritional components: It is a greening plant with extremely fragrant flowers, often cultivated in parks or near houses. The fresh flowers contain about 0.75-1.0% aromatic oil, which can be extracted to make Ying Zhao Hua concrete, used as a raw material for high-end perfumes, cosmetics, and soap fragrances, and also for scenting tea. The roots can be used medicinally to treat malaria.

name: Artemisia anomala
nutritional components: Contains volatile oils, mainly flavonoids, phenols, amino acids, etc. The whole plant is used medicinally. In southeastern provinces, it is known as 'Liu Ji Nu' or 'Nan Liu Ji Nu'. It has effects such as promoting blood circulation, regulating menstruation, clearing heat, detoxifying, reducing inflammation, relieving pain, and aiding digestion. It is used in folk medicine to treat intestinal, stomach, and gynecological diseases. In recent years, it has also been used to treat filariasis and can be brewed as a tea for its cooling and heat-clearing properties.

name: Vietnamese Berchemia
nutritional components: The roots, stems, or leaves can be used medicinally. They have effects such as dispelling wind, promoting diuresis, promoting blood circulation, relieving pain, and relieving cough and phlegm. They are mainly used to treat rheumatic joint pain, dysmenorrhea, postpartum abdominal pain, tuberculosis, acute and chronic bronchitis, jaundice, dysentery, traumatic injuries, fractures, and abscesses. Additionally, young leaves can be used as a tea substitute, and branches can be used to make nose rings for cattle.

name: Taiwan Gouercha
nutritional components: This species is distinguished by its smaller leaves with 6-8 lateral veins on each side; the sepals have a sharply narrowed short tip, differing from Kuling Gouercha. The roots are used medicinally for dispelling wind and dampness, dispersing blood stasis, reducing swelling, and relieving pain; farmers often use the branches to make nose rings for cattle; young leaves can be used as a tea substitute.

name: Big Fruit Gouercha
nutritional components: The leaf shape and drupe characteristics are the same as the original variety, but the leaves are hairless or only sparsely pubescent along the veins, or have tufts of hair in the vein axils, and the petioles are hairless, differing from the latter. The roots are used medicinally for dispelling wind and dampness, dispersing blood stasis, reducing swelling, and relieving pain; farmers often use the branches to make nose rings for cattle; young leaves can be used as a tea substitute.

name: Gouercha
nutritional components: The roots, stems, or leaves can be used medicinally. They are mainly used to treat rheumatic joint pain, dysmenorrhea, postpartum abdominal pain, tuberculosis, acute and chronic bronchitis, jaundice, dysentery, traumatic injuries, fractures, and abscesses. name: Kuling Gouercha
nutritional components: The roots are used medicinally to treat rheumatic pain.

name: Yunnan Gouercha
nutritional components: Commonly found in thickets or forests on slopes and by streams, at altitudes of 1500-3900 meters. The roots are used medicinally for dispelling wind and dampness, dispersing blood stasis, reducing swelling, and relieving pain; farmers often use the branches to make nose rings for cattle; young leaves can be used as a tea substitute.

name: Whorled-leaf Gesneria
nutritional components: The whole plant is used medicinally, with a sweet taste and warm nature, treating otitis media, bruises, and injuries.

name: Twin-gland Begonia
nutritional components: Has the effects of clearing heat, relieving cough, dispersing blood stasis, and reducing swelling. It is used to treat chronic bronchitis, lung heat cough, external high fever, tonsillitis, whooping cough, abscesses and sores, unknown swellings, and traumatic injuries.

name: Duckfoot Tea
nutritional components: The whole plant is used medicinally. Boiling the leaves in water and washing the body can treat colds. Boiling the roots with pig brain can treat headaches or malaria, and boiling with pig kidney and consuming with wine can treat back pain.

name: Black-faced God
nutritional components: The branches, leaves, and bark contain tannins, with the bark containing 12.02%. The leaves contain phenols and triterpenes. The seeds contain fatty oils. The roots and leaves are used medicinally to treat gastroenteritis, sore throat, rheumatic bone pain, eczema, hyperlipidemia, etc. Boiling the whole plant in water and washing externally can treat boils and dermatitis.

name: Calycopteris
nutritional components: The leaves are used as a tonic and detoxifying agent, consumed as a tea by women within 15 days after childbirth, and also used as wrapping leaves for tobacco. The fruit is used as a stimulant.

name: Middle East Golden Camellia
nutritional components: The seeds have a high oil content, and the tea leaves are widely enjoyed as a beverage. This species is similar to Camellia nitidissima Chi, but the leaves are shorter and smaller, elliptical, thin leathery, with inconspicuous serrations, which can be used to distinguish them.

name: Sharp-calyx Tumor-fruit Tea
nutritional components: This species differs from Camellia acutiperulata Chang in that the leaves are narrower, the flowers are shorter and smaller, the bracts are round, the sepals are leathery, and there are three styles. The seeds are hairy and have a high oil content.

name: Camellia acuticalyx
nutritional components: Found in evergreen forests at an altitude of 1,000 meters. This species has sharp bracts and sepals, a hairless ovary, and hairless seeds.

name: Camellia granthamiana
nutritional components: Grows in evergreen forests at altitudes of 200-250 meters. It has effects and benefits such as promoting appetite, refreshing the mind, and protecting the liver.

name: Camellia albosericea
nutritional components: Found in sparse mountain forests at an altitude of 1,550 meters. The leaves are relatively narrow, with fewer petals. The sepals and petals are covered with white silky hairs, and the ovary has 3 chambers. It has effects and benefits such as promoting appetite, refreshing the mind, and protecting the liver.

name: Camellia albopilosa

Ktze. in having larger flowers, more petals, and longer pedicels. It differs from Camellia purpurea Chang et Chen in having hairless sepals, larger fruits, and thinner fruit skin. It has effects and benefits such as promoting appetite, refreshing the mind, and protecting the liver.

nutritional components: The main effects and functions of Pu'er tea include refreshing the mind, calming the nerves, improving eyesight, quenching thirst, and promoting saliva production. It also helps in lowering lipids, reducing blood pressure, and decreasing uric acid levels.

name: Duo Mai Pu'er Tea

name: Nile crocodile
nutritional components: Crocodile meat is an excellent source of protein, with approximately 17.80 grams of protein per 100 grams of crocodile meat. The fatty acid composition in crocodile meat is balanced, containing monounsaturated fatty acids (MUFA) and polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFA) that are beneficial for cardiovascular health, such as ω-3 and ω-6 fatty acids. Crocodile meat contains various vitamins (such as vitamin A, E, B12) and minerals (such as calcium, phosphorus, iron, zinc), with particularly rich levels of vitamin B12 and zinc, which help support the immune system and skin health. Crocodile meat also has a high collagen content.

name: Chinese giant salamander
nutritional components: The muscles and skin of the Chinese giant salamander are rich in protein, accounting for more than 90% of its dry weight, and contain a variety of essential amino acids for the human body, making it a high-quality protein source. The amino acid profile in the salamander's muscles is complete, with 8 essential amino acids making up 44.40% of the total amino acids. The fat of the salamander has a high proportion of unsaturated fatty acids, especially polyunsaturated fatty acids such as docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), which are beneficial for cardiovascular health. The muscles and skin of the salamander contain various mineral elements, such as calcium, phosphorus, potassium, sodium, magnesium, zinc, iron, copper, manganese, and selenium, with selenium content meeting the standard for selenium enrichment, which positively enhances human immunity. The skin of the salamander contains a large amount of collagen and gelatin, which have positive effects on skin health and beauty. The salamander also contains functional components such as active peptides and polysaccharide peptides, which have effects such as regulating immunity, lowering blood pressure and lipids, improving corneal endothelium, and relieving fatigue.
